&nbsp;
The secretariat of the PD (which at the 'no' at the premierate will indicate the closure of the Rome campaign on 2 June) recalls that it is a reform that goes to impact on the prerogatives of the Head of State. If it is the stability you are looking for, adds Schlein, the Pd presented its counter-proposals to Meloni himself in the first and only meeting that was almost a year ago, not receiving answer. "We compared the government, the first and only in June 2023. We did not go empty-handed, but with six proposals to strengthen the stability of the executive: the constructive distrust that prevents you from throwing down a government without having an alternative majority. This avoids leaving the country in a dangerous crisis in the dark. They didn't even consider this proposal. Behind the decision of Giorgia Meloni there is a colossal deciduous for you." And then the 'no' of the dems is clearly and unhealthy: as long as there is the premiership there is no margin of comparison, but if the direct election of the President of the Council is removed from the table, "we are willing to always and everywhere confront". Meloni, however, looks ahead. The challenge, for the premier, remains the referendum: "Let's take the decision of the Italians. For a government chosen by the people is a government that responds to the people." It looks like an all in on the referendum already seen in the past. The previous is Matteo Renzi. The head of the executive, however, ensures that there is no personal interest in this game. And when the journalist asks her if she's worth it, Meloni answers: "I think so. I am not the kind of person who can repay with vanity the renunciations he has to do to cover this assignment. I get up in the morning, try to solve the problems and when I can go to sleep. There's nothing but the little time I can spend with my daughter on average an hour a day between morning and night. For me it is worth doing this life if when you're done you can look behind you, you can watch Italy.
&nbsp;
